SIMPLE: forfeit
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Forfeit
<hw>For"feit</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>forfet</ets> crime, penalty, F. <ets>forfait</ets> crime (LL.
<ets>forefactum</ets>, <ets>forifactum</ets>), prop. p. p. of
<ets>forfaire</ets> to forfeit, transgress, fr. LL.
<ets>forifacere</ets>, prop., to act beyond; L. <ets>foris</ets> out of
doors, abroad, beyond + <ets>facere</ets> to do. See <er>Foreign</er>,
and <er>Fact</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Injury; wrong;
mischief.</def> <mark>[Obs. & R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To seek arms upon people and country that never did us any
<qex>forfeit</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ld. Berners.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A thing forfeit or forfeited; what is or may be
taken from one in requital of a misdeed committed; that which is lost,
or the right to which is alienated, by a crime, offense, neglect of
duty, or breach of contract; hence, a fine; a mulct; a penalty; <as>as,
he who murders pays the <ex>forfeit</ex> of his life</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy slanders I forgive; and therewithal⟦br⟧
Remit thy other <qex>forfeits</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Something deposited and redeemable by a sportive
fine; -- whence the game of <xex>forfeits</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Country dances and <qex>forfeits</qex> shortened the rest of the
day.</q> <rj><qau>Goldsmith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Forfeit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Forfeit
<hw>For"feit</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>forfait</ets>, p. p. of
<ets>forfaire</ets>. See <er>Forfeit</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<def>Lost or alienated for an offense or crime; liable to penal
seizure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy wealth being <qex>forfeit</qex> to the state.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To tread the <qex>forfeit</qex> paradise.</q>
<rj><qau>Emerson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Forfeit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Forfeit
<hw>For"feit</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Forfeited</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Forfeiting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>forfeten</ets>. See
<er>Forfeit</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To lose, or lose the right
to, by some error, fault, offense, or crime; to render one's self by
misdeed liable to be deprived of; to alienate the right to possess, by
some neglect or crime; <as>as, to <ex>forfeit</ex> an estate by treason;
to <ex>forfeit</ex> reputation by a breach of promise</as>; -- with
<xex>to</xex> before the one acquiring what is forfeited.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[They] had <qex>forfeited</qex> their property by their
crimes.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Undone and <qex>forfeited</qex> to cares forever!</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Forfeit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Forfeit
<hw>For"feit</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be guilty of a
misdeed; to be criminal; to transgress.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To fail to keep an obligation.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will have the heart of him if he <qex>forfeit</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Forfeit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Forfeit
<hw>For"feit</hw>, <pos>p. p. ⟦or⟧ a.</pos> <def>In the condition of
being forfeited; subject to alienation.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Once more I will renew⟦br⟧
His laps⟦egrave⟧d powers, though <qex>forfeite</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Forfeitable</ent>⟦br⟧
